Here's the complete migration analysis and rewritten code for .NET 8:

---

## Pattern Classification

| Location | API | Pattern | Replacement |
|----------|-----|---------|-------------|
| `Stop()` | `Thread.Interrupt()` | Blocking call interruption | `CancellationToken.WaitHandle` |
| `Stop()` | `Thread.Abort()` | Timeout enforcement | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` |
| `RunLoop()` | `while (true)` | Cancellable work loop | `while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)` |

**Pre-existing bug found:** Multiple rapid `Enqueue()` calls only process one item per `WaitOne` wake â€” remaining items are stuck until the next `Enqueue`. The migration fixes this.

---

## Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
public class EventProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new();
    private readonly ManualResetEventSlim _newEvent = new(false);
    private readonly Queue<string> _queue = new();
    private readonly object _lock = new();
    private Thread? _thread;

    public void Start()
    {
        _thread = new Thread(RunLoop);
        _thread.Start();
    }

    private void RunLoop()
    {
        var token = _cts.Token;
        var handles = new[] { _newEvent.WaitHandle, token.WaitHandle };

        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            // WaitAny returns index: 0 = new event, 1 = cancellation
            WaitHandle.WaitAny(handles);

            if (token.IsCancellationRequested)
                break;

            _newEvent.Reset();

            // Drain all queued items (fixes original bug where
            // rapid Enqueue calls could leave items stranded)
            while (true)
            {
                string? item;
                lock (_lock)
                {
                    if (_queue.Count == 0)
                        break;
                    item = _queue.Dequeue();
                }
                Handle(item);
            }
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        lock (_lock) { _queue.Enqueue(item); }
        _newEvent.Set();
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        _cts.Cancel();          // signals token.WaitHandle, wakes WaitAny
        _thread?.Join(5000);    // wait for graceful exit
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts.Dispose();
        _newEvent.Dispose();
    }

    private void Handle(string item) { /* ... */ }
}
```

---

## Key Changes Explained

| What changed | Why |
|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` / `Thread.Interrupt()` â†’ `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` | Both throw `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 6+ |
| `ManualResetEvent.WaitOne()` â†’ `WaitHandle.WaitAny(event, token.WaitHandle)` | Allows `WaitOne` to wake on cancellation â€” not just on new events |
| `while (true)` â†’ `while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)` | Cooperative cancellation; thread checks the token each iteration |
| Added `IDisposable` | `CancellationTokenSource` and `ManualResetEventSlim` are `IDisposable` â€” leaking them causes timer/callback leaks |
| Inner drain loop added | Fixes pre-existing bug where back-to-back `Enqueue` calls left items stranded |

---

## Common Pitfalls

| Pitfall | How this code avoids it |
|---------|------------------------|
| `CancellationToken` not checked after `WaitAny` returns | Explicit `if (token.IsCancellationRequested) break` before processing |
| Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource` | `Dispose()` cleans up both `_cts` and `_newEvent` |
| Expecting cancellation to interrupt `Handle(item)` mid-execution | Cancellation is **cooperative** â€” if `Handle` is long-running, pass the token into it and call `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` at checkpoints |
| Using `Thread.Interrupt` as a "lighter" alternative | Also obsolete (`SYSLIB0046` in .NET 9); replaced entirely by the `WaitHandle` pattern |

> **If `Handle()` does long-running work**, pass the token through:
> ```csharp
> private void Handle(string item, CancellationToken token)
> {
>     // check at safe points inside heavy processing
>     token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
> }
> ```
